The core subject of this project includes national demographic information and economic conditions as well as healthcare delivery systems. World data functions as our analysis base to identify patterns which result in the generation of multi-dimensional visualization charts.

Code 
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_col, labs
import polars as pl  # Assuming you are using polars
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming unicef_data_meta is your Polars DataFrame
# Correct sorting in Polars
top5_life = unicef_data_meta.sort(by="Life expectancy at birth, total (years)", descending=True).head(5)

# Convert Polars DataFrame to Pandas for ggplot
top5_life_pandas = top5_life.to_pandas()

# Basic ggplot bar chart (no additional styling)
p = (ggplot(top5_life_pandas, aes(x='country', y='Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'))
     + geom_col()  # Basic bar chart
     + labs(title="Top 5 Countries by Life Expectancy", x="Country", y="Life Expectancy at Birth (years)")
)

# Save plot as image
p.save("life_expectancy_plot.png", width=6, height=4, dpi=100)

# Display the saved image
img = plt.imread("life_expectancy_plot.png")
plt.imshow(img)
plt.axis('off')  # Hide axes
plt.show()

The bar chart demonstrates fast which nations achieve the longest life expectancy thus providing an overview of worldwide health situations.

Code 
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, labs
import polars as pl  # Assuming you are using polars
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Convert your Polars DataFrame into Pandas
unicef_data_meta_pd = unicef_data_meta.to_pandas()

# Prepare X and y
X = unicef_data_meta_pd[["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"]]
y = unicef_data_meta_pd["Life expectancy at birth, total (years)"]

# Drop rows where X or y is NaN
data = pd.concat([X, y], axis=1).dropna()
X_clean = data[["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"]]
y_clean = data["Life expectancy at birth, total (years)"]

# Fit Linear Regression
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_clean, y_clean)
y_pred = model.predict(X_clean)

# Convert the predictions to a DataFrame for use in ggplot
predictions = pd.DataFrame({
    "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)": X_clean["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"],
    "Life expectancy at birth, total (years)": y_clean,
    "Predicted Life Expectancy": y_pred
})

# Create the scatter plot with the regression line using ggplot
p = (ggplot(predictions, aes(x='GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)', y='Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'))
     + geom_point(color='blue')  # Scatter plot for actual data
     + geom_smooth(method='lm', color='red', se=False)  # Regression line
     + labs(title="Scatterplot: GDP per Capita vs Life Expectancy with Regression Line",
            x="GDP per Capita (constant 2015 US$)", y="Life Expectancy at Birth (years)")
)

# Show the plot
display(p)

This scatterplot demonstrates the relationship between economic wealth (GDP per capita) and life expectancy. The regression line provides a clear visual of the positive correlation between these two variables.

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_line, geom_point, labs
import polars as pl  # Assuming you are using polars
import pandas as pd

# Convert your Polars DataFrame into Pandas
unicef_data_meta_pd = unicef_data_meta.to_pandas()

# Group by year and sum population
global_pop = unicef_data_meta_pd.groupby("year")["Population, total"].sum().reset_index()

# Create time-series line plot using ggplot
p = (ggplot(global_pop, aes(x='year', y='Population, total'))
     + geom_line(color='blue')  # Line plot
     + geom_point(color='red')  # Markers for each point
     + labs(title="Global Population Growth Over Time", x="Year", y="Population, total")
)

# Show the plot
display(p)

This time-series chart shows how the global population has increased year after year, highlighting global demographic growth trends across time.

import geopandas as gp
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_map

# Load the world shapefile from the URL
shape_world = gp.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")

# Convert your Polars DataFrame to Pandas
unicef_data_meta_pd = unicef_data_meta.to_pandas()

# Merge the shapefile with the UNICEF data (matching 'country' in your data with 'name' in the shapefile)
map_data = shape_world.merge(unicef_data_meta_pd, how='left', left_on='name', right_on='country')

# Create choropleth map without styling
(ggplot(map_data) +
    geom_map(aes(map_id='name', fill='GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'))
)

People use this mapping application to measure national economic power based on the global GDP per capita data. The economic standing of different nations becomes understandable through a color scheme that differentiates wealthy counties from the less fortunate ones.
